SIMPLE: excommunicate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Excommunicate
<hw>Ex"com*mu"ni*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>excommunicatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>communicare</ets> to
excommunicate; <ets>ex out + communicare</ets>. See
<er>Communicate</er>.]</ety> <def>Excommunicated; interdicted from the
rites of the church.</def> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>One
excommunicated.</def></def2>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou shalt stand cursed and <qex>excommunicate</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Excommunicate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Excommunicate
<hw>Ex`com*mu"ni*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Excommunicated</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Excommunicating</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To put out of communion;
especially, to cut off, or shut out, from communion with the church, by
an ecclesiastical sentence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To lay under the ban of the church; to
interdict.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Martin the Fifth . . . was the first that
<qex>excommunicated</qex> the reading of heretical books.</q>
<rj><qau>Miltin.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Excommunication</ent>⟦br⟧
